			<title>The Dying Earth Genre as Horror of the Irrational</title>
			<link>https://nightland.website/index.php/background/essays/185-the-dying-earth-genre-as-horror-of-the-irrational</link>
			<guid isPermaLink="true">https://nightland.website/index.php/background/essays/185-the-dying-earth-genre-as-horror-of-the-irrational</guid>
			<description><![CDATA[<h3 class="story-teaser">By Michael Caton</h3>
<div class="story-intro">
<p><a href="https://nightland.website/index.php/background/essays/185-the-dying-earth-genre-as-horror-of-the-irrational"><img class="story-thumb" src="https://nightland.website/images/thumbs/coady-dying-earth-horror-irrational-thumb.jpg" alt="beaten brass rings and a wrought iron spike spiralling down into the center of an orange vortex." /></a></p>
<p class="story-teaser">The horror these authors convey at the extinction of reason is at the core of dying Earth prose, more important I think than the used-up Earth or the cooling Sun, and it's this that strikes a chord of unease in many readers, children of the Enlightenment as we are.</p>
</div>
